<h3>Comparisons With Other Published Calendars</h3>
<p>The fasting dates on different Ananda Marga websites on the web are different. However, some of them use the exact same dates, although they are in different time zones:</p>
<ul>
    <li><a href="https://www.anandamarga.eu/fastingChart.php" target="_blank">Official Website of Ananda Marga in Europe - Berlin Sector</a></li>
    <li><a href="https://india.anandamarga.org/fasting-calendar/" target="_blank">Ananda Marga India - Delhi Sector</a></li>
    <li><a href="https://hks.amps.org/fasting-chart/" target="_blank">Ananda Marga Hong Kong Sector</a></li>
</ul>
<p>
    The fasting dates on the above web sites all correspond to the table below. These dates were compared to the calculation of this software.
    It can be concluded with high probability that the tithi times are based on Asia/Kolkata (Varanasi) time zone, as well as the chosen days for fasting.
</p>
<p>
    Comparisons were made using sunrise and the different types of dawn. The accuracy when comparing this software's calculations with the table below were:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>Astronomical Dawn: 82%</li>
    <li>Nautical Dawn: 82%</li>
    <li>Civil Dawn: 80%</li>
    <li>Sunrise: 78%</li>
</ul>
<p>
    Since astronomical dawn and nautical dawn had the same accuracy, astronomical dawn was the selected method to use.
    The rationale is that it makes the most sense if the beginning of the day is the actual beginning of something, and the astronomical dawn is the first dawn.
</p>
<p>
    The reasons 100% accuracy wasn't achieved:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>The calculations of tithis and sunrise are not exactly the same. Usually the difference is small, and still the chosen fasting day is different because tithi occurs almost exactly in between two solar days. </li>
    <li>Some of the official fasting days are miscalculated (probably mistaken because of human error).</li>
</ul>
